Exercise 2

Background

The dataset students2014 contains information from 166 students attending an introductory course at the University of Helsinki. Students answered questions regarding learning approaches. The data contains 7 variables: age, gender, attitude (the global attitude attitude toward statistics), deep (higher points indicate a strong need to engage in the actual content), stra (higher points indicate strategies used that maximices the the chance to get a high grade) , surf (higher points indicate an intention to get trough with least amonut of trouble) and points (Exam points).

students2014 <- read.table("~/GitHub/IODS-project/data/learning2018.txt", header=T, sep="\t")

Relationships

Figure 1 also shows correlation coffiecient for the each relationship between variables and scatteplots illustrating the relationship. The strongest correlation is between attitude and points, the variables are moderately positively correlated (Cor=0.437) and similar among women and men (Figure 1 and 2). A moderate negative correlations is observed between deep and surface questions (cor -0.324), which is considerably higher among men (Men: -0.622 vs women:-0.087, Figure 1 and 3). Linear regression

We run a linear regression to test how much attitude, age and gender explain the exam points. Of the included variables, there was only a statistically significant relationship between attitude and exam points (P=8.34e-09). Each increase 1 score increase in attitude increased the exam points by 3.6 points. Age and gender was removed from analysis, since they were did statistically significantly associate with exam points and the analysis was rerun.The attitude explained 18.56 % of the variability in Exam points.

my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude+age+gender, data = students2014)

Draw diagnostic plots

The Residual vs fitted plot is used to detect non-linearity, unequal error variances, and outliers, which linear regression assume there is not. Based on the plot it looks like there are some outliers.

The residuals ar located quite randomly around the 0 line, which suggest that the assumption that the relationship is linear correct.

three of residual stands out from the pattern of residuals, suggesting there are some outliers.

In the residuals vs leverege plot you can se that the outlier observations have a value of x that is far from the average of x.

The data is collected during the 2005-2006 school year from two public schools (secondary education) in Portugal. The data include student grades, demographic, social and school related variables, which were collected by using school reports and questionnaires.Among these is also alcohol use. Variables G1, G2, G3 are the grades from period 1 to 3 (3 is final grade). Range is from 0-20 and an description of the range of points is in table 1.

Step 3-4

Personal hypotheses

I chose the following interesting variables from the datset: sex, adress" (students home address type, rural or urban), famrel (from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent) and higher (wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)). My personal hypotheses regarding these variables and their effect on alcohol consuption is:

Students of male sex, with poor family relationships,that dont want to make a higher eduction and live in an urban environment drink more alcohol.

Numerical and graphical exploration of the variables

Based on a numerical exploration of the data, it seems that familial relationships are slightly better among non-high alcohol users (table 2a), as hypothesized. However, the mean alcohol intake seem to be higher among persons living in an rural envoronment(2b), which was unexpected. Those that wanted to take an higher eductation and persons of male sex had on average a higher alcohol intake (Table 2c-d). The same is also clear from the distribution figures of the selected variables (figure1a-d)

step 5

Logistic regression

Based on the summary of the fitted model, familial relationships are negatively associated with high alcohol use (P=0.02), having an urban address is negatively associatiod with alcohol but not on a statistically significant level (P=0.08), male sex is positively associated with high alcohol use (P=0.0002) and wanting to take a higher education is negatively associated (but not statistically significant!) with high alcohol use. The z- and p-values are based on the wald test, which is used in the model to test whether the pairwise difference between the coefficient and the reference class and the other class is different from zero or not (categorical values).

Table 3 contains the Odds ratios of the modelled variables (and 95%CI), which were calculated by taking the exponent of the coefficients. By looking at these, we can say that

  • For each increase(=improvement)in familial relationships there was 27% decrease in high use of alcohol, with the true population effect between 43% and 6%.
  • Persons having an urban address were 28% less likely to be high users of alcohol, however this observation was not statistically significant.
  • Persons of male sex were 142% more likely to be high user of alkohol (true population effect between 52% and 285%).
  • Persons who wanted to take a higher education were 44% less likely high alcohol users, however this observation was not statistically significant.
glm_res <- glm(high_use ~ famrel + address +sex+higher, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Step 6

The predictive power of the model

A 2x2 cross tabulation of predictions versus the actual values is found in tables and a graphic visualizing both the actual values and the predictions is in figure 4. 106 observations are predicted as false, even though they are true high users of alcohol (264 persons correctly predicted as non high alcohol users). Only 4 persons are falsely predicted as high alc users even though they are not, 8 persons are predicted correctly as high alc users. Model good at predicting non-high users, not so good at predicting high-users. The total proportion of inaccurately classified individuals (= the training error) is found in last table. Base on that table:

  • 69% is correctly identifed as non-high users

  • 2% correctly identified as high users.

  • 1% non-high users uncorrectly identified as high users

  • 28% high users uncorrectly identified as non high users

However, 71% is correctly identified, se better than guessing!

The average number of wrong predictions in the training data was 0.28

library(dplyr)
#fit a logistic regression with my sig variables
glm_res2 <- glm(high_use ~ famrel+sex, data = alc, family = "binomial")

#predict probability of high use
probabilities <- predict(glm_res2, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# see the last ten original classes, predicted probabilities, and class predictions
select(alc, famrel, sex, high_use, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data

Exercise 4

Step 2.Description of data

In step 1 I created a new chapter called chapter 4. The MASS library contains the Boston data set, which has 506 obs. of 14 variables. The 506 observations are records (housing values) for 506 neighborhoods (suburbs) around Boston.The following 14 variables are included in Boston:

  • crim : num per capita crime rate by town.
  • zn : num proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft
  • indus : num proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
  • chas : int Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • nox : num nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).
  • rm : num average number of rooms per dwelling.
  • age : num proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940..
  • dis : num weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
  • rad : int index of accessibility to radial highways..
  • tax : num full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.
  • ptratio: num pupil-teacher ratio by town..
  • black : num 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.
  • lstat : num lower status of the population (percent)..
  • medv : num median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

Relationships between variables in the data

Figure 2 shows the relationships between variables in Boston data, by looking at the correlations between the data. Tax is strongly (r2 above 0.7) positively correlated with rad (accessibility to radial highways) and proportion of non-retail businesses (indus). Crim rate in the suburbs correlate postively with accesibility to radial highways and higher taxes.Overall, there are quite many moderate-strong correlations between some of the variables, could these correlations sets form clusters?

Step 5: Linear discriminant analysis

Fited the linear discriminant analysis on the train set. Used the categorical crime rate as the target variable and all the other variables in the dataset as predictor variables. Figure 3 shows the LDA (bi)plot.

About linear discriminant analysis: Target variable is categorical and this classification method tries to find the variables (or finds the (linear) combination of the variables) that disciminate/sepratate the classes/groups in the target variable best.But it can be also used to predict classes in the new data. Assumptions: variables are normally distributed, variables have same variance and that is the reasons variables were scaled previously

#lda of trained data
lda.fit <- lda(crime~ ., data = train)
lda.fit

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Step 6: Predict crime classes in test using LDA

The classes was predicted with the LDA model on the test data. In the Cross you can see the results with the crime categories from the test set. Based on that you can see:

  • Of the 32 of the suburbs with class low crime rate, 14 was correctly predicted (44%, so less than half), however, predictions were not far away: the rest 18 suburbs with class low crime rate was predicted to have a medium low crime rate. Not too bad!

  • Of The 20 suburbs with medium low crim rates, 16 (80%) was predicted to have medium low crime rate > quite good!

  • Of the 23 suburbs with medium high crime rates, 14 (61%) was correctly predicted, 2 (9%) was predicted wronlgy as high and 7 wrongly as medium low (30%). Not as good as the previous class but better than the first.

  • The predictions of crime rate class high performed best! All 27 (100%) correctly predicted as high.

library(MASS)
#classe from 
correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)
lda.fit <- lda(crime~ ., data = train)

Step 7:k-means clustering

There are different ways to determine if observations are similar or dissimilar to each other. Distance measure can be used for this, and I used dist(), which has as default the most common distance measure the Euclidean distance. The distances were saved to object dist_eu. After distances were calculated k-means was run on the dataset. K-means is easy and often find a solution, however a small change in the dataset can produce a very different result.

First how the total of within cluster sum of squares (WCSS). When you plot the number of clusters and the total WCSS, the optimal number of clusters is when the total WCSS drops radically. The optimal numbers of clusters is 2, according to figure below.

I find it really hard to interpret the results otherwise. But some of the variables show similar patterns, for example nox rm and age seem to cluster.

##Reload the Boston dataset and standardize
library(MASS);library(ggplot2)
data('Boston')
boston_scaled2 <- as.data.frame(scale(Boston))


##Calculate the distances between the observations (Euclidian)
dist_eu <-dist(boston_scaled2)
summary(dist_eu)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4625  4.8241  4.9111  6.1863 14.3970
##Run k-means algorithm on the dataset
# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(Boston, centers = 3)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(Boston, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)
